{{Use British English|date=July 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}} {{Infobox company | name = DC Studios Inc. | logo = | type = [[Privately held company|Private]] | industry = [[Video game industry]] | fate = [[Dissolution (law)|Dissolved]] | successor = [[Firebrand Games]] | founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1999|12|03}} in [[Glasgow]], Scotland | founder = Mark Greenshields | defunct = {{End date|df=yes|2007|09|25}} | hq_location_city = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]] | hq_location_country = Canada | key_people = Mark Greenshields {{small|([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])}} | num_employees = 55 | num_employees_year = 2006 }}
'''DC Studios Inc.''' was a British-Canadian [[video game developer]] based in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]]. Originally founded in [[Glasgow]], Scotland in December 1999, the company later expanded to Montreal, [[Edinburgh]], Scotland and [[Dublin]], Ireland. In May 2005, the company acquired ''[[State of Emergency 2]]'' from the defunct [[VIS Entertainment]]. The game released to severe financial underperformance, as a result of which all DC Studios operations in the United Kingdom were halted, leaving only the Montreal studio with 55 employees, which in turn shut down in September the following year.
== History == DC Studios was founded on 3 December 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/five-years-old-and-financially-fit |title=FIVE YEARS OLD AND FINANCIALLY FIT |author= |date= |website=gamesindustry.biz |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> It was set up in [[Glasgow]], Scotland by Mark Greenshields,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/focus-on-dc-studios-mark-greenshields |title=Focus On: DC Studios' Mark Greenshields |author= |date= |website=gamesindustry.biz |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> who previously left [[Steel Monkeys]], another Scotland-based development studio.<ref name="Steel Monkeys">{{cite web |url=https://www.scotsman.com/business/companies/media-leisure/director-leaves-brother-s-games-company-to-join-rival-1-1292170 |title=Director leaves brother's games company to join rival |author= |date= |website=scotsman.com |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> In November 2000, the company expanded with a second outfit located in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/technology/british-game-developer-takes-business-to-new-level-in-montreal/article1184775/ |title=British game developer takes business to new level in Montreal |author= |date= |publisher= |accessdate=1 July 2018 |via=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> In August 2003, Andrew McLennan left his position as [[commercial director]] from Steel Monkeys, at the time run by his brother Derek as [[managing director]], to join DC Studio as [[business development]] director.<ref name="Steel Monkeys" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/92948/DC_Studios_Appoint_New_Biz_Dev_Director.php |title=Gamasutra - The Art & Business of Making Games |first=David |last=Jenkins |date= |website=www.gamasutra.com |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> In April 2005, DC Studios opened a government-funded development studio in [[Dublin]], Ireland, seeking to employ 50 further staff.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/96238/DC_Studios_Creates_GovernmentApproved_Irish_Wing.php |title=Gamasutra - The Art & Business of Making Games |first=David |last=Jenkins |date= |website=www.gamasutra.com |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref>
In May 2005, the company acquired the rights to ''[[State of Emergency 2]]'' from previously defunct [[VIS Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scotsman.com/business/companies/media-leisure/new-state-of-emergency-declared-as-glasgow-firm-takes-on-game-1-1389794 |title=New State of Emergency declared as Glasgow firm takes on game |author= |date= |website=scotsman.com |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/dc-studios-picks-up-state-of-emergency-2 |title=DC Studios picks up State of Emergency 2 |author= |date= |website=gamesindustry.biz |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> Following its release, however, the game severely underperformed in sales, due to which DC Studios announced on 4 June 2006 that it had ceased all operations in the United Kingdom, laying off all staff, including 29 from its [[Edinburgh]] offices.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/default_content/12435428.State_Of_Emergency_spells_end_for_29_staff_GAMING__REDUNDANCIES/ |title=State Of Emergency spells end for 29 staff GAMING: REDUNDANCIES |author= |date= |website=HeraldScotland |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/100540/DC_Studios_Closes_Scottish_Development_HQ.php |title=DC Studios Closes Scottish Development HQ |first=David |last=Jenkins |date= |website=gamasutra.com |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> Only their Montreal office remained open, holding 55 staff.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/news060606dcstudios |title=DC Studios shuts down |author= |date= |website=eurogamer.net |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> That Montreal office was finally shut down in favour of opening a [[Merritt Island, Florida]] office for Greenshields' newer venture, [[Firebrand Games]], on 25 September 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mcvuk.com/development/montreal-is-not-an-efficient-place-to-run-a-business |title='Montreal is not an efficient place to run a business' |author= |date= |website=mcvuk.com |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/106573/Race_Game_Developer_Firebrand_Gets_US_Office.php |title=Race Game Developer Firebrand Gets U.S. Office |first=Brandon |last=Boyer |date= |website=gamasutra.com |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref>
