{{Infobox album| | name = Da Drought 3 | type = Mixtape | artist = [[Lil Wayne]] | cover = Da Drought 3 cover.jpg | alt = | released = April 13, 2007 | recorded = | venue = | studio = | genre = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]] | length = 108:06 | label = [[Young Money Entertainment|Young Money]] | producer = | prev_title = [[Like Father, Like Son (Birdman and Lil Wayne album)|Like Father, Like Son]] | prev_year = 2006 | next_title = [[The Leak]] | next_year = 2007 }} '''''Da Drought 3''''' is a double-disc [[mixtape]] by [[Lil Wayne]], released on April 13, 2007. It is widely regarded as one of the best mixtapes of all time, receiving rave reviews from ''[[Rolling Stone]],'' [[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]], and [[MTV News]].
== Background == This is the third in the trilogy of mixtapes in ''Da Drought'' series. Released in 2007, the mixtape was delayed slightly as a result of Wayne's last-minute decision to add songs to the album's second disc. The album is available as a free legal download. It only contains remixes of other songs. It is noted for Lil Wayne's use of [[similes]], liquid [[non sequitur (humor)|non sequiturs]], and [[metaphors]].<ref name=pitchfork/>
When speaking to [[MTV]] about the double mixtape, Lil Wayne stated that he did not plan on two discs being released until he found how many songs he had recorded. He also stated he did not have a preconceived plan on how to choose the songs:
{{cquote|The radio be on and whatever song comes on, add that instrumental to it.<ref>[http://www.mtv.com/bands/h/hip_hop_week/2007/hottest/index12.jhtml MTV News: Hottest MCs In The Game 2] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080316054025/http://www.mtv.com/bands/h/hip_hop_week/2007/hottest/index12.jhtml |date=2008-03-16 }} ''[[MTV]].com'' Accessed November 30, 2008.</ref>}}
== Reception == {{Album ratings |rev1 = [[AllMusic]] |rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/da-drought-3-mw0001603881|title=Da Drought 3 – Lil Wayne|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=September 23, 2018|last=Purdom|first=Clayton}}</ref> |rev2 = ''[[MSN Music]]'' |rev2score = A<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cg2008-03.php|title=Consumer Guide|work=[[MSN Music]]|date=March 2008|accessdate=September 23, 2018|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau}}</ref> |rev3 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' |rev3score = 8.5/10<ref name=pitchfork>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/10229-da-drought-3/|title=Lil Wayne: Da Drought 3|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=May 16, 2007|accessdate=September 23, 2018|last=Dombal|first=Ryan}}</ref> |rev4 = [[Sputnikmusic]] |rev4score = 4.5/5<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/25761/Lil-Wayne-Da-Drought-3/|title=Lil Wayne – Da Drought 3|publisher=[[Sputnikmusic]]|date=May 26, 2008|accessdate=September 23, 2018|author=joshuatree}}</ref> |rev5 = ''[[Stylus Magazine]]'' |rev5Score = B+<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/lil-wayne/da-drought-3.htm|title=Lil Wayne – Da Drought 3 – Review|work=[[Stylus Magazine]]|date=May 10, 2007|accessdate=September 23, 2018|last=McGarvey|first=Evan|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20160102013218/http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/lil-wayne/da-drought-3.htm|archivedate=January 2, 2016}}</ref> |rev6 = ''[[URB (magazine)|URB]]'' |rev6score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.urb.com/2007/04/24/lil-wayne-da-drought-3/|title=Lil Wayne – Da Drought 3|work=[[URB (magazine)|URB]]|date=April 24, 2007|accessdate=September 23, 2018|archiveurl=http://archive.is/1FXT|archivedate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> }}<!-- Automatically generated by DASHBot--> Da Drought 3 received acclaim from critics and was hailed as the best mixtape of 2007 by MTV News. Lil Wayne was officially named The "Hottest MC" by their hip hop brain trust.<ref>[http://www.mtv.com/bands/h/hip_hop_week/2007/hottest/index11.jhtml MTV News: Hottest MCs In The Game 1] ''[[MTV]].com'' Accessed November 30, 2008.</ref> It was also nominated for mixtape of the year at the Ozone Awards but lost to [[Killer Mike]]'s ''[[I Pledge Allegiance to the Grind]]''.{{Citation needed|date= November 2008}} The album was #27 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]'''s list of the Top 50 Albums of 2007.<ref>Robert Christgau, David Fricke, Christian Hoard, Rob Sheffield (December 17, 2007). [https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/17601851/the_top_50_albums_of_2007/27 "The Top 50 Albums of 2007"] ''Rolling Stone''. Retrieved December 20, 2007</ref> [[Online magazine|Online music magazine]] [[Pitchfork Media]] placed ''Da Drought 3'' at number 99 on their list of top 200 albums of the 2000s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/7708-the-top-200-albums-of-the-2000s-100-51/|work=[[Pitchfork Media]]|author=Pitchfork staff|title=The Top 200 Albums of the 2000s: 100-51|date=September 30, 2009|accessdate=October 1, 2009}}</ref>
