[[File:Latchis Hotel & Theatre Brattleboro.jpg|thumb|The Latchis Hotel and Theatre]]
The '''Latchis Hotel and Theatre''' (orig. the '''Latchis Memorial Building''') is an [[Art deco buildings|art deco building]] in [[Brattleboro, Vermont]] first built in 1938.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://vermontartsliving.com/?p=1201|title=A new look for the heavens and the earth|last=|first=|date=|website=Vermont Arts and Living|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-05-10}}</ref> The building is one of only two extant Art Deco buildings in Vermont.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2HGZnONS1YwC&pg=PA320&lpg=PA320&dq=latchis+hotel+and+theatre&source=bl&ots=SpJfI1sqrd&sig=4UIffHmqTTIepUcKX3B7FAP5Syg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjV-LDXuOTTAhVCbSYKHciKBZo4KBDoAQhKMAk#v=onepage&q=latchis%20hotel%20and%20theatre&f=false|title=DK Eyewitness Travel Guide: New England|last=Berman|first=Eleanor|date=2010-07-01|publisher=Penguin|year=|isbn=9780756666729|location=|pages=320|language=en}}</ref> The building is run by the '''Brattleboro Arts Initiative''', a local non-profit.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://valleyadvocate.com/2009/06/11/the-latchis-artfully-sustained/|title=The Latchis: Artfully Sustained|last=Roessler|first=Mark|date=2009-06-11|website=Valley Advocate|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-05-10}}</ref>
The building was constructred as a memorial to [[Demetrius P. Latchis]], a Greek immigrant who became an important businessman in Brattleboro, by his sons.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.benningtonbanner.com/stories/helena-leschuk-greets-hotel-guests-with-warmth,506602|title=Helena Leschuk greets hotel guests with warmth|work=The Bennington Banner|access-date=2017-05-10|language=en}}</ref> Latchis had built a business which ran fourteen theatres throughout New England.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u6-5CAAAQBAJ&pg=PA22&lpg=PA22&dq=latchis+hotel+and+theatre&source=bl&ots=Rzqw7UfM0c&sig=AXNpLKk7AUX-mzPMkf-M9WBdq-M&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjV-LDXuOTTAhVCbSYKHciKBZo4KBDoAQhHMAg#v=onepage&q=latchis%20hotel%20and%20theatre&f=false|title=Vermont Curiosities: Quirky Characters, Roadside Oddities & Other Offbeat Stuff|last=Wilson|first=Robert|date=2008-10-14|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=|isbn=9781461747246|location=|pages=22|language=en}}</ref> The interior include murals and other artwork with Greek mythology,<ref name=":0" /> which was created by Hungarian muralist [[Louis Jambor]].<ref name=":1" /> The building also includes [[terrazzo]] flooring.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.latchishotel.com/blog/history-lesson-latchis-family-theater-empire-built/|title=History Lesson: The Latchis Family & The Theater Empire They Built. - Latchis Hotel|date=2016-08-24|work=Latchis Hotel|access-date=2017-05-10|language=en-US}}</ref> The building was designed so that it could include a hotel, theatre, ballroom, restaurant, bar, and other business spaces.<ref name=":1" /> The architect for the building was [[S. Wesley Haynes]].<ref>Naylor, David. ''Great American Movie Theaters''. 1987.</ref>
Though a successful business through the 60s, the business slumped in the 70s.<ref name=":1" /> In 1985, two children of the original brothers revitalized the hotel.<ref name=":1" /> They sold the hotel in 2003 to a local non-profit, the Brattleboro Arts Initiative, created for maintaining the building, bought the hotel for 1.3 million dollars.<ref name=":1" /> The money included both local and federal grants.<ref name=":1" /> The building suffered considerable damage in 2011, during [[Hurricane Irene]], but was reopened later that year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.reformer.com/stories/a-dried-out-latchis-hotel-and-theater-will-reopen,400765|title=A dried out Latchis Hotel and Theater will reopen|last=Stilts|first=Josh|date=|work=The Brattleboro Reformer|access-date=2017-05-10|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref> The building was further restored in 2013, after a half-million dollar fundraising campaign.<ref name=":0" />
