[[File:Hacksaw-Jim-Duggan-Entrance,-RLA-Melb-10.11.2007 filtered.jpg|right|thumb|200px|alt=A white man running, wearing blue shorts and boots, while in a professional wrestling four-sided ring holding a pole with both hands.|[[Jim Duggan|Hacksaw Jim Duggan]] was the final [[WCW World Television Championship|WCW World Television Champion]]]]
The '''[[WCW World Television Championship]]''' was a [[professional wrestling]] [[Professional wrestling championship#Gimmick/style championships|world television championship]] owned by the now-defunct [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotion]].

The title was introduced on February 27, 1974 in [[Mid-Atlantic Championship Wrestling]] (MACW), a territory of the [[National Wrestling Alliance]] (NWA). MACW, also known as [[Jim Crockett Promotions]] (JCP), was purchased by [[Turner Broadcasting System]] in 1988, and subsequently renamed WCW. In March 2001, certain assets of WCW were sold by [[AOL Time Warner]] to the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF, now WWE). As such these assets, including the rights to the WCW World Television Championship, inactive since April 10, 2000, were now WWF property.<ref name="wwfbuywcw">{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/SlamWrestlingWCWSale/cyrus_01mar25-sun.html|title=Deal leaves wrestlers out in cold|last=Callis|first=Don|date=2001-03-25|work=SLAM! Sports: Wrestling|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|accessdate=2009-11-25}}</ref> Before it was known as the WCW World Television Championship (starting in 1991 and continuing until the title's deactivation), it was known as the NWA Mid-Atlantic Television Championship (1974 to 1977), the NWA Television Championship (1977 to 1985), and the NWA World Television Championship (1985 to 1991).

Being a professional wrestling championship, it was won via a scripted ending to a match or awarded to a wrestler because of a [[Narrative thread|storyline]]. All title changes occurred at JCP or WCW-promoted events. The inaugural champion was Danny Miller, who defeated [[Ole Anderson]] on February 27, 1974, in the finals of a tournament. [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] holds the record for most reigns, with six. [[Ricky Steamboat|Rick Steamboat]]'s second reign ended due to vacancy for unknown reasons. The day on which the reign ended is also unknown, although it is known that the reign began on June 10, 1978, and came to a close sometime in 1980. As such, if the reign ended on January 1, 1980, or any later time during 1980, then Steamboat's second reign is the longest in the title's history, at over 570 days.<ref group="N" name="Vacant1"/> Five different reigns are tied for the record for shortest reign in the title's history, at one day.

[[Jim Duggan]] was the last champion in his only reign. At the time, then-champion [[Scott Hall]] did not want to be champion, and after unsuccessfully trying to give the title to [[Kevin Nash]], he abandoned the title by throwing the championship belt into a trashcan on the November 29, 1999, episode of one of WCW's television programs, ''[[WCW Monday Nitro|Nitro]]''.<ref name="Hallbio"/> Duggan later found the championship belt in a dumpster on the February 16, 2000, episode of another of WCW's television programs, ''[[WCW Saturday Night]]'' and named himself champion.<ref name="WCWTVrevived"/> The championship was later retired on the April 10, 2000, episode of ''Nitro'', after a storyline reboot by WCW authority figures [[Eric Bischoff]] and [[Vince Russo]]. Overall, there were 107 reigns shared among 55 wrestlers, with 11 vacancies.

